## The Three Things You Need to Know First

Before anything else, these three concepts are the foundation of everything in this guide.

An IP address is the ID card your device or object has. It is how it gets recognized and how it communicates with everything else.

A subnet mask is the room in which your object and other objects reside in. It defines the boundary of who belongs to the same space as you.

A default gateway is the door that allows traffic from your room to go to and from the outside world. It needs to have an ID card that belongs in the same room as your objects because your objects need to be able to reach the door first before they can send anything out. If the door had a foreign ID card your objects would not even recognize it as their door. And the gateway does not just connect to the internet specifically, it is the door to anywhere outside your room, whether that is another room in the same building or the internet itself.

---

## What Does an IP Address Actually Look Like

Now if you take an object in your subnet room and you look at the ID plastered onto it you will see four numbers, for example 192.168.10.1. What do those weird numbers mean? Its simple, those four numbers are also a set of numbers with an assigned value like if your ID card said wooden chair it would also say what kind of wood it is, date acquired, condition and price. But for our IP address they are octets so its groups of 8 bits per number you see on an IP address. To make it stick better lets take the 192, in its octet form it is 11000000. Now why is that? Its because each 1 represents a different value, always in this order: 128, 64, 32, 16, 8, 4, 2, 1. So every number in the four part arrangement you see in an IP address is just a combination of those bits adding up. So when you see 255.255.255.0 in a subnet mask, which is your room, its the highest a single octet can go because 11111111 means all bits are switched on.

Now your ID card actually has two parts printed on it. The room number, which tells you which room you belong to, and the seat number, which is your specific spot inside that room. The subnet mask is the key that tells you where one ends and the other begins. The 1s are saying this part is the room number and the 0s are saying this part is the seat number. So for 192.168.10.1 with a mask of 255.255.255.0, the 192.168.10 is the room number and the 1 is your seat number. That is why a /24 room can only hold 254 seats. The last octet gives you 256 combinations but seat 0 is the rooms own nameplate, it identifies the room itself and not any device inside it, and seat 255 is the megaphone that everyone in the room hears at once which is the broadcast address. So those two are taken, leaving 254 for actual devices. The rule is always 2 to the power of however many host bits you have, minus 2.

