## Classful Subnetting

Although this method of subnetting is now replaced by other more relevant forms, this is still relevant whenever you hear people talk about what kind of address they are interacting with. This was also a method of describing an IP address as its related to its subnet mask. You can imagine if two people are talking about the objects in their room and they are talking about certain ID cards being class A, it means those default subnet masks (rooms) have 8 bits for the network but 24 for the host. A class B is split evenly with 16 for the network and 16 for the host and last but not least for the class C addresses they have 24 for the network but only 8 for the host.

So it looks like this:

```
Class A: 255.0.0.0     (network.host.host.host)
Class B: 255.255.0.0   (network.network.host.host)
Class C: 255.255.255.0 (network.network.network.host)
```

But yeah this hasn't been used since 1993 for subnet masking purposes, although for learning the basics or in casual conversation you will still hear these terms. And for the critical function being that its used as a starting point when subnetting our networks, its like you are the engineer for the said building we are talking about, we all have to start provisioning the room space so this is one way to start the plan drawing process.

### The Class Chart

Now you know what kind of default subnet masks are there, how is it related to our ID cards or IP addresses? Well, a neat way for you to recognize what kind of class an ID card belongs to is to look at its first set of bits, so here is a chart to help you out:

```
Class A   Leading bits: 0xxx  (0-127)
Class B   Leading bits: 10xx  (128-191)
Class C   Leading bits: 110x  (192-223)
Class D   Leading bits: 1110  (224-239)  Multicast
Class E   Leading bits: 1111  (240-255)  Reserved
```

Class D ones are assigned to multicast communication and what is that? It is a network transmission method where data is sent from one sender to multiple specific recipients all at the same time. It is like if the landlord of your building wanted to notify specific rooms about something important, so he photocopies one letter and slides it under multiple specific doors simultaneously. Not every door, just the ones that need to know.

Class E ones are reserved by IANA, the guys who make all of this IP addressing wizardry possible, but for their own researching purposes.

### Factory Exercise: Sorting ID Cards

So to test our newly found knowledge, I am taking you back to this factory scenario. Pretend that you are a factory worker and your boss decided to order you to sort out a bunch of spare ID cards:

**19.36.21.10** — The first decimal is within the range of 0-127 so it is going to be a class A ID card.

**222.255.190.120** — We can sort it out as a class C ID card because its in the range of 192-223. But remember when talking to other people about this always use the proper terms so you can be consistent and your studying way more effective.

**165.245.0.1** — This is a class B ID card because the range it is in sits right in the middle.

**128.200.3.1** — This is a class B ID card but sometimes you might slip up and think it is a class A one so its really important to remember the extreme ranges for each class.

**191.1.2.50** — Another ID card to trip you up but yeah this is still in the extreme upper range of a class B address range.

**192.168.1.0** — And lastly this ID card is within the class C range because it starts at 192.

So now your boss is satisfied that you were able to sort the remaining ID cards and now you can go back to work on your main job.

### The Four Values You Need

So as much as you hate math, it is imperative we figure out how to calculate the IP subnet and for that we kind of have 4 values we need to know in order to pull this off. It is like as we figure out the space within the room where our objects are located, some special objects related to this room are needed for us to figure out.

### Network Address

The first of which is the IP address or ID card associated with something we call the Network Address. This is the one that defines all of the other objects in our room. Now why is it important to determine? Its a special ID card that allows us to figure out more information about the room we are in. To solve for the network address, you just take the host bits and switch them all to 0. Done and dusted.

To make things easier on us we will have a set of examples, we have 192.134.12.80, 10.23.45.2 and 154.112.67.69. Quick reminder, reference the subnet masks for each respective class of address accordingly.

Since it is a class C address it has 24 bits to the network while only having 8 for the host, we can immediately chuck the 80 out of here and switch it to 0:

```
192.134.12.80
255.255.255.0
192.134.12.0
```

```
10.23.45.2
255.0.0.0
```

Class A addresses only have one octet for the network and the rest is for the host, since thats the case we can just eliminate the three numbers after the 10:

```
10.0.0.0
```

```
154.112.67.69
255.255.0.0
```

This one is class B so therefore half of it is now out the window:

```
154.112.0.0
```

Thats literally how easy it is to figure out what your network address is. And also I want to reiterate how important it is to get. your. classifications. right.

### First Usable Host

The second piece of the puzzle is the first usable host address on a subnet. Its basically what it sounds like, a regular ID card but its the very first one either you or the DHCP robot butler can give out. The way you can sniff out this particular ID card is to just make it one number higher than the network address:

```
10.0.0.0      ->  10.0.0.1
192.134.12.0  ->  192.134.12.1
154.112.0.0   ->  154.112.0.1
```

### Broadcast Address

Now the third piece is what we call the broadcast address. What is it pray tell? Its an ID card thats used to send information to ALL objects in the same specific room or subnet. Thats why its called a broadcast because it sends stuff to everyone. To find this one is also very easy, its the inverse of how we find the network address. So remember our switch analogy? For that we just take all the switches or octets that belong to the host and turn them all on which means changing them to 1. And if you remember, whats the decimal value for all the switches being turned on? Its 255. So let me show you what it is:

```
192.134.12.0  ->  192.134.12.255
10.0.0.0      ->  10.255.255.255
154.112.0.0   ->  154.112.255.255
```

### Last Usable Host

For the last and final piece we need to find the last usable host. Now this is also the inverse of the first usable host because duh. Its also just an ID card that is the last within a network that you can get. The way you get it is by taking the broadcast address and just shaving one off. So it will look something like this:

```
192.134.12.255  ->  192.134.12.254
10.255.255.255  ->  10.255.255.254
154.112.255.255 ->  154.112.255.254
```

Although we don't use this kind of subnetting anymore, we can still use the foundational aspects behind it when we are looking at stuff that is class or non class based. And as we go on with the different methods of subnetting you will notice why classful subnetting is useful for understanding the process because it will just be used over and over again regardless of the IP address and the subnet mask.

