## Classless Subnetting and CIDR

### Why Classful Died

So if since 1993 we haven't used class based subnetting what the heck are we using then? Its a special thing called CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) and the dreadful slash notation, which we are going to get into in just a sec.

To give you a reason why we don't use class based subnetting anymore I can sum it up in one sentence, although you can do your own research on this topic if you are curious. Too many addresses were being allocated especially to businesses that it sucked the supply so fast it was endangering the growth of the internet. Think in terms of having 16 million class A addresses for IBM but they only have a few thousand computers. That fiasco at scale meant multiple businesses who were getting class A and class B blocks sucked the supply extremely fast.

If you didn't understand that here is another example. If we had no way of distributing commodities precisely, lets say like fuel, and everyone is forced to get 5 barrels every time they went to a gas station, not only would it be really expensive but it dries up the oil supply faster than anyone could manage. And so only a handful of people can get fuel which is way more than what they will need while the rest of us are holding the bag.

### What CIDR Actually Is

As we go back to CIDR and slash notations, we have to also know how they work specifically. So if classful subnetting relied on giving every buyer of a room a whole building, with CIDR we can choose precisely how many rooms we need, where do we want these rooms and how do we want these rooms. Its frankly a marvel of networking engineering but necessary nevertheless.

So it goes like this, for example here is a random class C subnet mask:

```
255.255.255.0
```

We obviously know it has 24 bits to the network and 8 to the host. 24... and thats exactly what CIDR is in example. It shows you the bits allocated for a particular subnet. So the CIDR notation for our example subnet mask would look like this:

```
192.168.1.0/24
```

That is what you will generally see and type in its full form. But we will deal with weird numbers and notations because some like /13, /22 or /21 are all not multiples of 8. In exchange for being weird, CIDR gives us precision to allocate exactly what we need.

The subnet mask as Professor Messer said is just a series of ones on the left and zeros to the right, true to the binary math primer above. So if you have 255.255.255.0 you would count how many ones are associated with the subnet mask:

```
11111111.11111111.11111111.00000000
```

In this case its 24 bits to network while 8 to host so its slash notation version is /24. So a neat analogy for it would be to just simply count the number of switches turned on. But here is a weird number:

```
11111111.11111111.11110000.00000000
```

Most people would initially do a double take when this is introduced traditionally but remember always go back to the switch analogy. We just need to count the amount of turned on switches right now and to make things faster, focus on the incomplete octet and add that number to the number of complete octets which are times 8. So we have 4 switches turned on but we have two full batches of switches turned on already so two batches times 8 is 16 plus 4 is 20 and our CIDR notation would be /20. The first 20 bits or switches would belong to the network while the 12 remaining would belong to the host.

Another example to drive the weirdness home:

```
11111111.11111111.11111111.11100000
```

Using that same method, you would just take 4 seconds to figure out that this array of switches has 27 switches turned on. So the CIDR notation would be /27.

### Reading Weird Numbers

We have looked at subnet masks in binary form so far and we can now figure out the CIDR notation stuff but we often refer to the subnet mask in decimal instead. If we were to convert these numbers into decimals there are only a certain number of values you would ever run into:

### The Octet Value Chart

```
00000000  =  0
10000000  =  128
11000000  =  192
11100000  =  224
11110000  =  240
11111000  =  248
11111100  =  252
11111110  =  254
11111111  =  255
```

Although there is a shortcut method, when you are taking the AZ-104 exam every second matters and so does remaining mental capacity. If preferable you would want to write this down so you can save time. Using this chart will make converting the weird ones to decimal really fast, but as you practice more and more you will grow out of it eventually and will allow you to use the faster methods like 7 second or magic number. There are levels to this. If we want to be better at designing how big a room can be in our analogy we have to learn the basics of interior design and blueprinting first. If we jump over to the good kinds of designing we won't appreciate it as much compared to working our way up from there.

So putting it together:

```
11111111.11111111.11110000.00000000
255      255      240      0
```

With the chart we were able to immediately solve the subnet mask being 255.255.240.0 and its CIDR notation being /20 just by cross referencing the chart. One last example:

```
11111111.11111111.11111111.11100000
255      255      255      224
```

Another easy weird number to figure out. So we have 255.255.255.224 and its notation is /27. So when you just see weird numbers out here and you need to convert it to decimal form in the wild you can now at least do it correctly.

### A Quick But Important Detour

Whenever you are trying to configure a device or in this case taking an object from the outside and putting an ID card on it, you are going to need to put in the IP address, subnet mask, default gateway and the DNS servers (covered in a later topic). A useful tidbit is that on Windows they generally want you to type the whole decimal thing but on a router or switch it might be expecting the CIDR notation so instead of 255.0.0.0 you will just need to type /8. But of course check and double check. I always want you to know that double checking is really important whenever you do anything, even in this. So yeah, back to the main topic.

