## Magic Number Subnetting

The magic number subnetting method exists so we can do the necessary calculations without writing a thesis dissertation when solving a networking problem. Admittedly, you will need a chart or two to pull this off correctly in your first few tries but certain factors will come into play to help you not only get used to pulling these numbers out of nowhere but making sure you save a lot of time in the process. Even doing this crudely will save you more time than doing it via the binary conversion method in the classless section.

The magic number literally is a single value that gives you all the info you need about a subnet and to answer those pesky configuration problems. Its like if you were already figuring out the range of ID cards you can put in your room you wouldn't necessarily need to draw the room and cards over and over. You would use a computer and memorize a bit of values to do the heavy lifting for you.

Just like in the classful subnetting section there are four key pieces of information we need to get:

- Network Address
- Broadcast Address
- First Usable Host
- Last Usable Host

So all in all we are trying to reach the same destination but in a new context thanks to classless but using a huge shortcut via the magic number method.

### Reference Charts

Charts will help you on your journey here but as the more you deal with these numbers the more intuitive it gets:

```
CIDR to Decimal (partial):
/9  - 255.128.0.0
/10 - 255.192.0.0
/11 - 255.224.0.0
/12 - 255.240.0.0
/13 - 255.248.0.0
/14 - 255.252.0.0
/15 - 255.254.0.0
/16 - 255.255.0.0
/17 - 255.255.128.0
and so on...
```

```
CIDR by Interesting Octet Position:

CIDR for I.O. 2    /9   /10  /11  /12  /13  /14  /15  /16
CIDR for I.O. 3    /17  /18  /19  /20  /21  /22  /23  /24
CIDR for I.O. 4    /25  /26  /27  /28  /29  /30
Magic Number       128   64   32   16    8    4    2    1
Subnet Mask        128  192  224  240  248  252  254  255
```

> Note: There is no /31 or /32 in the magic number chart because /31 leaves only 2 addresses (useful only for point-to-point links) and /32 leaves nothing for the host.

### The Steps

1. Convert the subnet mask to decimal if necessary because some questions will give it to you in binary form
2. Find the Interesting Octet = anything that is not 255 or 0
3. Calculate the Host Range
4. Identify the Network Address
5. Identify the Broadcast Address
6. Get the first usable host address
7. Get the last usable host address

### Magic Number Practice Problem One

```
IP address:   165.245.77.14
Subnet Mask:  255.255.240.0
```

To solve this, a solving chart would help us visualize and set a foundational flow as to what is actually going on here. We need to do it two times to find the Subnet ID (which for solving purposes acts like the Network Address) and then the Broadcast Address.

```
Mask        255.255.240.0
Action
IP          165.245.77.14
Subnet ID
```

The rule here is if its 255, just copy the IP address and if its zero then let it be zero:

```
Mask        255.255.240.0
Action      Cy   Cy        Ze
IP          165.245.77.14
Subnet ID   165  245        0
```

The octet with the 240 fulfills the conditions of not being either 255 or zero. Thats our interesting octet. The next thing we have to do is use this interesting octet as a subtrahend against 256. Now why 256 instead of 255? Its because 256 is 0 to 255, so in numerical form it does end in 255 but the amount of values are 256 since 0 is included. So the answer of 256 - 240 is 16 and that means there are 16 hosts on this particular subnet. A reference chart for intervals based on your magic number is necessary here:

```
Interval Chart (magic number 16):
0   16   32   48   64   80   96   112   128   144   160   176   192   208   224   240   256
```

If we look at the IP address number on our interesting octet we will see its 77. We can use that value to estimate that our subnet ID is between 64 and 79. To figure out the subnet ID we can just take the first number of that range which would be 64:

```
Mask        255.255.240.0
Action      Cy   Cy   Eq  Ze
IP          165.245.77.14
Subnet ID   165  245  64   0
```

And there you have it, the subnet ID is done. But we are not done yet since we also need to figure out the broadcast address:

```
Mask          255.255.240.0
Action
Subnet ID     165.245.64.0
Broadcast
Address
```

To kick things off we do things like how we did it before. If its 255 just copy the subnet ID, however if its 0 instead of copying zero we substitute for 255. And also, the weird octet out in our subnet mask is the same interesting octet.

```
Mask          255.255.240.0
Action        Cy   Cy        Su
Subnet ID     165.245.64.0
Broadcast     165  245       255
Address
```

Just the same as before we use the equation of (256 - Interesting Octet) to find the magic number which is 16. Now we take the Subnet ID in the interesting octet column and then add the magic number to it and then subtract 1. So its 64 + 16 = 80 - 1 = 79. Thats the answer to the missing space on our broadcast address. The reason the equation exists is because addresses start from zero, so if we just add to get 80 we would already be in the next subnet. But we are trying to find the broadcast for this subnet so we subtract one to find the very last address for the block size.

```
Mask          255.255.240.0
Action        Cy   Cy   Su
Subnet ID     165.245.64.0
Broadcast     165  245  79  255
Address
```

And there you have it, we have the subnet ID and the broadcast address. To get the first and last usable address we just add one to the interesting octet of the subnet ID and subtract one from the broadcast address.

```
First Usable Address:  165.245.64.1
Last Usable Address:   165.245.79.254
```

### Magic Number Practice Problem Two

```
IP address:   192.168.13.0
Subnet Mask:  255.255.255.240  (/28)
```

This one is a little different from the first problem because the interesting octet is now in the fourth position instead of the third. But the method is exactly the same, so lets get to it.

```
Mask        255.255.255.240
Action
IP          192.168.13.0
Subnet ID
```

Just like before we follow the same rules. If its 255 copy the IP and if its 0 let it be zero. The 240 is our interesting octet because its neither 255 nor 0.

```
Mask        255.255.255.240
Action      Cy   Cy   Cy
IP          192.168.13.0
Subnet ID   192  168  13
```

Now we calculate the magic number: 256 - 240 = 16. So our interval chart looks like this:

```
0   16   32   48   64   80   96   112   128   144   160   176   192   208   224   240   256
```

The fourth octet of our IP address is 0 which sits right at the start of the first interval block between 0 and 15. So our subnet ID for the interesting octet is just 0.

```
Mask        255.255.255.240
Action      Cy   Cy   Cy   Eq
IP          192.168.13.0
Subnet ID   192  168  13    0
```

Now for the broadcast address we do the same thing as before, copy the subnet ID where its 255 and substitute 255 where its 0.

```
Mask          255.255.255.240
Action        Cy   Cy   Cy   Su
Subnet ID     192.168.13.0
Broadcast     192  168  13   255
Address
```

Now we apply the equation: Subnet ID of interesting octet + magic number - 1. So its 0 + 16 - 1 = 15.

```
Mask          255.255.255.240
Action        Cy   Cy   Cy   Su
Subnet ID     192.168.13.0
Broadcast     192  168  13   15
Address
```

```
Subnet ID:          192.168.13.0
Broadcast Address:  192.168.13.15
First Usable Host:  192.168.13.1
Last Usable Host:   192.168.13.14
```

Notice how the method did not change at all even though the interesting octet moved to a different position. That is the whole point of the magic number method. Once you know the steps it does not matter where the interesting octet is hiding.

