## Seven Second Subnetting

I want to kind of revise what I said about subnetting methods having levels. There are pros and cons between this method and the magic number method but the reason I said levels is also because of one thing: just in case. The magic number method allows us to quickly determine how big a room is and how many objects it can fit inside by using logic, simple math and deduction on established rules. So if you are in a pinch and you are trying to design a room without a pen and paper you have a way of doing so.

This is where the seven second subnetting method comes into play. If the magic number method uses logic, simple math and deduction to make things easier for us, this method takes a different approach to the problem of subnetting quickly. It relies more on your memorization skills because we will frontload all of that deduction effort into a single chart. The idea being, if we were still designing a room to put all our objects and ID cards in, we would just use a different program with a bunch of templates already installed so we won't do a lot of thinking.

As per usual, for finding out the first and last usable host address on the subnet, we will add and take from the network and broadcast address respectively. For both methods its kind of a non-negotiable rule because you have no other way of figuring it out and logically it makes sense.

This method is extremely useful for one key use case: exams. Would you rather logic and reason your way through when you could be using your precious time on more complex questions on the AZ-104? Hell no. This allows us to still get correct answers while saving time and brainpower. Structurally this comes after the magic number method because the previous method introduced us to network intervals. But if you are really good at it someday, it doesn't matter what method you use unless its the slow and tedious binary conversion method, because it will be second nature to you to subnet networks accurately.

Subnetting as a whole is just splitting a network into smaller sizes and this is important to reiterate and remember because you can't use the chart without it. So it can be not split, or split between 2, 4, 8 and more ways.

### The Seven Second Chart

```
Masks (each horizontal CIDR group represents which octet they belong to respectively):

               SubnetM    Networks    Addresses
/1  /9  /17  /25   128        2          128
/2  /10 /18  /26   192        4           64
/3  /11 /19  /27   224        8           32
/4  /12 /20  /28   240       16           16
/5  /13 /21  /29   248       32            8
/6  /14 /22  /30   252       64            4
/7  /15 /23  /31   254      128            2
/8  /16 /24  /32   255      256            1
```

**Networks** = how many subnets you get when you split the network
**Addresses** = how many total addresses are in each subnet

### How to Use the Chart

Lets say you got a /21 on the subnetting problem you have. So your subnet mask is 255.255.248.0. Now why is that? Its because whenever you are choosing a value in the chart you are choosing the last available turned on switch in the switch array. All switches before the last switch in the CIDR notation you are given are considered on. However why is there a 0 on the end? It still follows the switch analogy perfectly because in the third octet you have both turned on and off switches meanwhile on the last octet you have no turned on switches at all so there is no value to display. Another example is /7 so its mask would be 254.0.0.0 or /15 which would be 255.254.0.0.

The Networks and Addresses columns correspond to the row level of the CIDR notation you have. More likely than not you will be dealing with weird notations both in the AZ-104 exam and professionally. In those weird octets, you are going to use the CIDR you are given to refer to how you are going to split the 256 network and how many addresses are in each, because you will refer to that with your given IP address to note which block interval yours belongs to, therefore helping you find the network and broadcast address of your subnet.

So lets say you have a /25 IP address. Your subnet mask is going to be 255.255.255.128 and the IP address you were given has the number 112 on the fourth octet. Since /25 is in the first row, it tells you the network is split in 2 and the range is 0-127 and 128-255. 112 belongs to the first half so your network address starts with 0 since thats the first number of the block while your broadcast is going to be 127 since its the last address in the block.

Quick reminder that you can also draw these intervals by hand so you can pinpoint it correctly but for speed purposes you should only draw them when necessary. The main chart you draw no matter what.

### Seven Second Practice Problem One

```
180.140.32.200/21
```

First we get the subnet mask:

```
180.140.32.200
255.255.248.0
```

The switch logic explains why the rules are set up this way because the third octet has incomplete switches on while the fourth is dead. Same as magic number, if its 255 then copy it, if its 0 then substitute with zero:

```
180.140.32.200
255.255.248.0
180.140.   .0
```

You will notice how the third space is left empty. This is where our CIDR notation comes into play. /21 gives us 32 networks with 8 addresses for each, now if we draw that up:

```
0   8   16   24   32   40   48   56
```

We now have an impromptu interval chart for this specific problem. A trick to be more efficient is to only draw a little over the interesting octet IP address number. Now if we check the third octet of the IP address we see 32. This is where you might get confused with what the answer is:

```
180.140.32.200
255.255.248.0
180.140.32.0
```

You would probably think why not just a 24 on the third octet? Well here is the explanation. 24 is the starting point of the subnet right? But here its the starting point of the last subnet and that subnet only ends at 31. But 32 is both the value we are using and the starting point of the block interval. Now we got that out of the way we can work on the broadcast address.

Same as the magic number we just copy on the 255s and substitute on the 0 with a 255:

```
180.140.32.200
255.255.248.0
180.140.  .255
```

But unlike the magic number we don't have to do another math problem because we made a chart and an impromptu interval chart as well. If 32 is the starting point of our current subnet then 39 is the last point. Which would make our broadcast address look like this:

```
180.140.32.200
255.255.248.0
180.140.39.255
```

And par for the course our first and last usable host addresses look like this:

```
First Usable:  180.140.32.1
Last Usable:   180.140.39.254
```

### Seven Second Practice Problem Two

```
192.172.13.50/27
```

This one is a little different from the first because our interesting octet is now in the fourth position instead of the third. But as always, the method does not change.

First we get our subnet mask and since /27 is in the third column of our chart we know immediately that our subnet mask is:

```
192.172.13.50
255.255.255.224
```

Same rules apply, if its 255 copy it and if its 0 substitute with zero. Unlike the first problem all of our first three octets are 255 which means we copy all of them and the interesting octet is sitting right there on the fourth position:

```
192.172.13.50
255.255.255.224
192.172.13.
```

Now /27 tells us from the chart that we have 8 networks with 32 addresses each so our impromptu interval chart looks like this:

```
0   32   64   96   128   160   192   224
```

Now we check the fourth octet of our IP address which is 50 and we line it up against our interval chart. 50 sits right between 32 and 64 which means 32 is the starting point of our block. So our network address looks like this:

```
192.172.13.50
255.255.255.224
192.172.13.32
```

Now for the broadcast address, same as before we copy the 255s and substitute the 0 with 255 leaving the interesting octet empty again:

```
192.172.13.50
255.255.255.224
192.172.13.  .255
```

Now since 32 is our starting point and our block size is 32, the last address in this block is 63. So our broadcast address is:

```
192.172.13.50
255.255.255.224
192.172.13.63
```

And par for the course our first and last usable host addresses are:

```
First Usable:  192.172.13.33
Last Usable:   192.172.13.62
```

And that is the seven second subnetting method. Two problems, two different octet positions, same method both times. Once that chart is memorized and the interval logic clicks, you will be flying through subnet problems on the AZ-104 without breaking a sweat.

### Usable Hosts and Azure Reserved Addresses

Seems funny I forgot to mention the number of usable hosts. To get that we take our original CIDR notation, refer to the Addresses column on the row level and then subtract two, or five when we are in Azure.

Why two? Those belong to the network and broadcast addresses.

Why five in Azure? Azure reserves three additional addresses on top of those two:

- The second address for the default gateway
- The third for Azure DNS
- The fourth is a spare reserved Azure DNS address

