## Azure Relevant Information

### What is a Virtual Network

Now I want you to go back to our metaphor of a room. Then I want you to zoom out in your mind and imagine a building filled with rooms lined up properly. But this building is surrounded by an impossible sea of water and only special methods can access it so it can talk to mainland. That is a rudimentary idea of what a virtual network is.

A virtual network for all intents and purposes is an isolated building on an island in your tiny planet called an Azure subscription and in a tiny region that is well, your region. With that in mind, your little building cannot span towards other planets or regions. However it can span within other buildings within your region.

### Address Spaces and Subnets in Azure

Initially this building is going to have a shipment of allocated ID cards to it. Its called a CIDR block of a range of IP addresses. You can also add additional ranges as you are configuring this virtual network in the Azure portal. But if you added too much when configuring, as long as there are no subnets in the IP range you can just take them off saving you on costs and network allocations.

Now you have a VNet but it is just one building. A normal building has multiple segmented rooms. Thats where when you configure your virtual network, you can also configure how many subnets you want. But remember that your configured subnets are always going to get their stuff from the original allocated ID cards given to you by Azure. And you can't use the same IP range for two or more subnets. Think of it this way, if you were stranded in the train station would you really give your train ticket to a random stranger and tell them both of you can share it? Hell no. Its the same idea here. You can break up the range as your needs demand but never share. Azure does automatically suggest you a range when you are configuring in the settings but you can adjust those to your liking.

Like for example here. Azure gives you this default range of 10.0.0.0/16 so its going to be 10.0.0.0 to 10.0.255.255 because as you remember during our previous sections these two figures are the network and broadcast ranges respectively.

Also shown in the portal when you are configuring, you will see a subnets section. For this example the subnet is named default with an IP range of 10.0.0.0 to 10.0.0.255/24 (256 addresses) which coincides with our CIDR notation. Now as a beginner this is why subnetting is important. As you go on to your real job or on the exam you need to be able to understand how to provision these resources, or at the very least have a high birds eye overview of how these addresses are being allocated. Also if you are planning to put a public facing service then it also allows you to put a NAT gateway which is basically one of the special methods I mentioned that your isolated island can communicate to the outside world or planet.

### RFC 1918 in Azure

Usually you are going to use RFC 1918 and if you forgot what that is, its part of the IPv4 addressing section where I mentioned that this was a way to make sure private networks can communicate to each other effectively. Now since this is completely private it doesn't matter if another company is using those addresses the same way you do since you are both isolated from each other. I recommend you Google the full ranges so you can understand more.

A random tidbit but you can also use internet compatible IP ranges for your VNet in Azure. This is a rich mans problem since it requires you to have your own public address block which to be fair you can lease but at this scale its mostly businesses that do these sort of shenanigans. But when you do allocate, these addresses do not become internet routable.

### Reserved Addresses in Azure

There are also some IP addresses with certain ranges that you cannot use because Azure needs them to keep your subscription and services running:

```
x.x.x.0    Network address
x.x.x.1    Default gateway
x.x.x.2    Azure DNS mapping to VNet space
x.x.x.3    Azure DNS mapping to VNet space
x.x.x.255  Broadcast address
```

These are the ones mentioned earlier but in more detail. So whenever you check your subnets the available IP addresses will only be 251 at most for a /24 notation.

### Azure Reserved System Addresses

These specific ones are used by Azure themselves for the services they offer:

```
168.63.129.16/32   Public IP for internal DNS, health probes, and Azure Load Balancer
169.254.169.254/32 Azure Instance Metadata Service (IMDS) endpoint
169.254.0.0/16     Link-local addresses
127.0.0.0/8        Loopback addresses
224.0.0.0/4        Multicast traffic
255.255.255.255/32 Broadcast address
```

This is not recommended but the smallest you can go when provisioning ID cards is /29 because it will give you three IP addresses but that dries up really quickly so its better to go for a bit more buffer like /27 or /26.

### Subnet Delegation

Now some services will do this but when you check a certain subnet in the portal it might say Delegated to X service. What does that mean? Well if you imagine a room, this room has a notice on its door saying for exclusive use only by Azure Management. But this just applies to some services to promote tight integration and the tradeoff is it wants its own room to work properly.

### Connecting Resources to Your Virtual Network

After discussing all of these things, I want to walk you through the premise of connecting your resources in Azure to your virtual network. Why? So your resources or objects within a subnet can talk to each other. Like a virtual machine that has a network interface card that gives it connectivity. But that same virtual machine can have more than one NIC so it can talk to multiple subnets, which gives you more wiggle room for that resource to be used. But remember those NICs have to be in the same VNet. Its like a guy who knows a lot of people but those people don't know each other at all.

Or a different use case: a network virtual appliance that wants its hands on multiple subnets because that appliance and service requires it to. One example is Azure Firewall which gives you protection as long as you route your traffic through it, so you would be incentivized to let it hook towards multiple subnets.

### Availability Zones and Subnets

I want to add for the last part that subnets span regions and a concept called availability zones which we will call cities. I won't go too in depth on that but basically its 3 data centers within a region to make sure we have resiliency and redundancy against disasters or what not. So I can have multiple resources in different availability zones but they can still belong to the same subnet. This kind of material is covered more by AZ-900 stuff so I do recommend for you all to check them out and keep studying.

